    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Modern historians view the UN's effectiveness in stopping major 21st-century wars as a qualified failure, largely due to the paralysis of the Security Council. The organization is consistently undermined by the veto power wielded by permanent members, which allows great power politics to override collective security efforts. While the UN excels at humanitarian aid and peacekeeping in smaller conflicts, its structural limitations prevent it from preventing large-scale interstate wars. Therefore, its role is more accurately described as a necessary but often impotent diplomatic forum.",
